text: In regard to earlier comments, I feel led to say this. We are equal! Black, White, Latino, Asian. It doesn't matter what color you are, it's how you act. Ignorance is one thing, and you can fix it. Stupidity is quite another, it's not correctable. I am white, but I don't judge people by what they look like, I judge them based on their character. I don't want to be judged by my skin color, so why would I judge someone else for the same thing. I try not to judge at all, but it is humanly impossible. My point is, treat others as you want to be treated. I'm sorry if this somehow offends someone, but I feel I needed to say something. God bless everyone.

Just know that it is not only an incredible work of art on film, but one that through its story, retold by Misan Sagay & filmed by Amma Asanta, allows for those audience members viewing its' contents, an opportunity to understand, forgive, and heal. As an African American, who has lived through decades of America's historical transitions—know that I do not use my words lightly. For those who wish to either rent or purchase the film "Belle", might I suggest that you go to iTunes, and look under the heading of movies, where you should be able to immediately purchase the film from the iTune Store.

text: Not that I wouldn't appreciate Tom Felton as an actor, but I want to point out that this is a really good movie concerning plot and how the topic is handled. It's not pretending everyone's nice and without prejudice, it shows the injustice of this world and that there is hope, because some people will always want to change it. I think this movie isn't only great, because it shows an aspect of that era that is not often found in movies, it also makes us aware of the fact that racism was and is a part of our society and that we should stand up for the right thing, that we are all the same - all human beings in the end.

text: From what this film presented, I felt it was quite...weak. Its not nearly as compelling as the trailer. Belle knew her family didn't "approve" of her, but she never sought out any connection with the people she looked like? Like, ever? I find that hard to believe, especially when the most compelling scene in the film is when she's getting her hair combed. Everything that dealt with her torn identity seemed to be through a white lens, as if this woman wouldn't at least be curious. But I don't know, thats what I got from this film at least.

Dido's mother was a slave of a Spanish slave ship round the Caribbean. Her father died with no legitimate heirs and left what he could to her.  It's ok that they portrayed the English and Europe to be racist, they absolutely were and in most cases are, it is realistic and a reality. I think the movie would have been better had they not ridiculed her Caucasian cousin at every turn. You can tell a black person made this movie. The white, very rich, titled, and very BEAUTIFUL Lords didn't want to marry her (although they would pick her above all other nobility) because of their prejudice and other people's prejudice although they found her beauty to be so great. Give me a break. The maker of this movie didn't do justice there. The maker should have been a lot harsher on the white people for their racism but not by this ridiculousness of making them act ridiculous but by actually showing more of the disgust and reproach they felt. During this time people couldn't even stand to be in the same room with a black person, wouldn't even hire them. The servants were worse snobs too. To the world, they were a slave breed. And it would take a very liberal sort of person, with peculiar tastes to view them as equals or marry them. An anomaly at that time. And you'd only see white men marrying black or mixed woman, not the other way around, because guys like a damsel in distress and for woman to be beneath them anyway, especially during that time. If a white girl married a black man it had to be because he was very rich and she poor so you never saw this.  Also, I think Dido should also have been portrayed just a little snob-like at times too. She must have noticed her family's standing was higher than others.  If only black people, mostly westernized black people, were more proud of Africa, you would see many films of black people in Africa during this same time period, but I never find dramas or novellas like those.

However, when I finally saw the movie, I was greatly disappointed; my expectations were incredibly high, and I admit, the movie is a bit slow and boring, in some ways. But because I loved the trailer so profoundly, I decided to give it another go, and I'm SO glad I did. Each time I watch it, the story gets better and better. text: How interesting that this was based on a real person. Obviously, like all historical films, it takes some liberties but the fact that an admiral in the late 1700s actually DID take his mixed-race daughter to to England to be brought up as a free gentlewoman seems incredible to me. Mixed-race children weren't exactly unusual in those days - many white men had 'flings' with black women - but so many of them were just abandoned by their fathers. How heart-warming to know that there were some who did care.
